node.text:
Due to #COVID19 my Spring 2020 graduation was cancelled, along with my graduation pictures. I finally got to take a few graduation photos and man did it feel good to commemorate graduating with my Doctorate of Public Heath.
.
.
.
From 2002 to 2017, of the roughly 50,000 people who earned Ph.D.s each year, the % who are black increased only from 5.1% to 5.4%. I’m a honored to be considered in that number and I encourage anyone considering a PhD to go for it! I’ve learned not only the ins and outs of public health but also a tremendous amount about the journey to finding myself. When I started the program I felt unsure and unworthy of obtaining a PhD. Throughout the program I pushed myself to limits I never knew were possible, I changed and blossomed into the young woman I am today. Along my journey I’ve nourished some incredible relationships and I’ve learned some amazing lessons, which I’ll share with you all!

1. Find yourself before you try to find anyone else. If you don’t know what you want out of life then how can you expect to find someone who compliments you?
.
.
.
2. The only limit you have are the ones you make up. Don’t let yourself hold you back from achieving your goals.
.
.
3. It’s okay to take mental breaks from “the grind”, no once can be on point 24/7, you need time to refuel and refocus. Me and @_janberry took about two semesters off during our PhD journey because we needed to refuel, and I don’t regret any of it!
.
.
.
4. Never stop learning. Whatever field you’re in I’m sure some part of it changes and grows everyday, when you stop learning and growing with it then you stop being relevant and risk losing touch with the world. But remember #1, know yourself so you’re not easily influenced and swayed by things of the world.
.
.
